{"title_page": "Equestrian statue of the Duke of Wellington, City of London", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Equestrian statue of the Duke of Wellington, Royal Exchange|the statue in Royal Exchange Square, Glasgow|Equestrian statue of the Duke of Wellington, Glasgow|other monuments to Wellington|List of monuments to Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| title              = Equestrian statue of the Duke of Wellington\n| italic title       = no\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      = \n| wikidata           =\n| image              = London, UK (August 2014) - 175.JPG\n| image_upright      = .9\n| alt                = \n| caption            = The statue in 2014\n| artist             = Francis Leggatt Chantrey\n| year               = {{start date|1844|06|18}} \n| completion_date    =  <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| catalogue          = \n| medium             = Bronze\n| movement           =\n| subject            = Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington\n| height_metric      =  <!-- (i.e. in metric units) -->\n| width_metric       = \n| length_metric      = \n| diameter_metric    = \n| height_imperial    =  <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) -->\n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| diameter_imperial  = \n| dimensions         = \n| dimensions_ref     = \n| metric_unit        = cm  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| imperial_unit      = in  <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included -->\n| weight             = \n| designation        = \n| condition          = \n| museum             = \n| city               = London\n| coordinates        = {{Coord|51|30|39|N|0|5|16|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title, inline}}\n| mapframe           = yes\n| mapframe-zoom      = 13\n| owner              = \n| accession          = \n| preceded_by        =  <!-- preceding work by the same artist -->\n| followed_by        =  <!-- next work by the same artist -->\n| module             = \n| website            =  <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\nThe '''equestrian statue of the Duke of Wellington''' is an outdoor sculpture of [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]], a [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] soldier and statesman, located at the [[Royal Exchange, London|Royal Exchange]] in London.<ref name=LR>{{cite web|title=Statue: Duke of Wellington statue \u2013 EC2|url=http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/duke-of-wellington-statue-ec2|publisher=LondonRemembers.com|accessdate=22 September 2014}}</ref> It overlooks [[Bank junction]] in the historic [[City of London]]. The sculptor was [[Francis Leggatt Chantrey]].<ref name=\"Baker2002\">{{cite book|author=Margaret Baker|title=Discovering London Statues and Monuments|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pVJLa5jgzQ4C&pg=PA151|year=2002|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-0-7478-0495-6|page=151}}</ref> The statue commemorates Wellington's assistance to the City of London in ensuring that a bill was passed to allow the rebuilding of [[London Bridge]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://barryoneoff.co.uk/html/statues2.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831010011/http://barryoneoff.co.uk/html/statues2.html |archive-date=31 August 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhile sitting for a later portrait by [[Charles Robert Leslie]], Wellington recalled that Chantrey had told him he had a square head.<ref name=\"Gleig1865\">{{cite book|author=George Robert Gleig|title=The life of Arthur, Duke of Wellington|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Y5QAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA442|year=1865|publisher=Longmans, Green, Reader, and Dyer|page=442}}</ref> After Chantrey's sudden death his studio assistant [[Henry Weekes]] completed the sculpture.<ref name=odnb>{{cite web |title = Stevens T. 'Weekes, Henry (1807\u20131877)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (2004) |url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/28969 |publisher= Oxford University Press| accessdate = 2014-09-22}}</ref><ref name=LR/>\n\nWellington attended the unveiling of his statue on 18 June 1844.<ref name=\"Baker2002\"/><ref name=\"Timbs1852\">{{cite book|author=John Timbs|title=Wellingtoniana: anecdotes, maxims, and characteristics, of the duke of Wellington, selected by J. Timbs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BghcAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA66|year=1852|page=66}}</ref> The date was chosen to commemorate the [[Battle of Waterloo]], where Wellington led an allied army to victory against [[Napoleon]], in 1815.<ref name=\"Wilson1844\">{{cite book|author=Effingham Wilson|title=Wilson's Description of the New Royal Exchange, Including an Historical Notice of the Former Edifices: And a Brief Memoir of Sir Thomas Gresham, Knt., Founder of the Original Burse in the Reign of Queen Elizabeth ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RrpCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA114|year=1844|publisher=E. Wilson|pages=114\u2013116}}</ref> [[Frederick Augustus II of Saxony|Frederick Augustus II]], [[King of Saxony]], who was in London visiting [[Queen Victoria]], also attended the unveiling.<ref name=\"Wilson1844\"/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Statue Of The Duke Of Wellington-Royal Exchange-London.jpg|thumb|Close-up of the statue in 2004]]\n\nThe [[equestrian statue]] was erected to show the City's gratitude for Wellington's help in assisting the passage of the London Bridge Approaches Act 1827. This Act led to the creation of [[King William Street, London|King William Street]].\n\n\"Wellington\" is inscribed on each side of the plinth; on its ends is the inscription \"Erected June 18, 1844\". A brass plaque at the plinth's base reads:\n\n{{Quote| On 19th July 1838 the Court of Common Council of the City of London agreed to a contribution of \u00a3500 toward the cost of the above statue of the Duke of Wellington in appreciation of his efforts in assisting the passage of the London Bridge Approaches Act 1827. This Act led to the creation of King William Street. The government donated the metal, which is bronze from captured enemy cannon melted down after the Battle of Waterloo, and valued at the time at \u00a31500. The total cost of the statue was \u00a39000. The remainder being raised by public subscription.<br/>\nThe sculptor, Sir Francis Chantrey (1781 to 1841), was commissioned in 1838 but died before the work was completed. It was finished by his assistant Henry Weekes (1807 to 1877).<br/>\nThe Lord Mayor, William Magnay, unveiled the statue on 18th June 1844, the anniversary of Waterloo, in the presence of his guest the King of Saxony.\nAdjoining the statue, a piece of granite from London Bridge (1825 to 1967) has been set into the pavement by the Corporation of London. The elevational stonework from the same bridge was re-erected over the Colorado River in Lake Havasu City, Arizona, USA, in 1971.<ref name=LR/>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|London|Visual arts}}\n* {{Commons category inline|Equestrian statue of the Duke of Wellington, Royal Exchange, London}}\n\n{{Wellington}}\n{{Public art in London}}\n\n[[Category:1844 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1844 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Equestrian statues in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in the City of London]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed monuments and memorials]]\n[[Category:Military memorials in London]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in London]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in London]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in the United Kingdom|Wellington, London]]\n[[Category:Statues in London]]\n[[Category:Statues of Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|London, City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Equestrian statue of the Duke of Wellington, Royal Exchange|the statue i